---
import BaseLayout from "../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import FlavorTabs from "../../../components/FlavorTabs.astro";
import ModuleHero from "../../../components/module/ModuleHero.astro";
import ModuleFooterNav from "../../../components/module/ModuleFooterNav.astro";
import ModuleQuiz from "../../../components/module/ModuleQuiz.astro";
import { flavor as gcp } from "../../../data/flavors/gcp";
import { flavor as aws } from "../../../data/flavors/aws";
import { flavor as azure } from "../../../data/flavors/azure";
import { flavor as oss } from "../../../data/flavors/oss";

const moduleId = "00-foundations";
const entries = {
  gcp: gcp[moduleId],
  aws: aws[moduleId],
  azure: azure[moduleId],
  oss: oss[moduleId],
};
---

<BaseLayout title="00 · Foundations">
  <article>
    <ModuleHero moduleId={moduleId}>
      <p>
        Before touching any cloud service, get the vocabulary straight. Every later module assumes you know these
        five ideas cold.
      </p>
    </ModuleHero>

    <h2>Tokens</h2>
    <p>
      LLMs don't read characters or words — they read <strong>tokens</strong>, sub-word chunks produced by a
      tokenizer. Pricing, context limits, and latency are all measured in tokens, not characters. A rough rule of
      thumb for English text: 1 token ≈ 4 characters ≈ ¾ of a word.
    </p>

    <h2>Embeddings &amp; vector similarity</h2>
    <p>
      An embedding model maps a chunk of text to a fixed-length vector such that semantically similar text lands
      close together in that vector space. "Similar" is measured with a distance metric — usually cosine similarity
      or dot product. This is the mechanism that lets retrieval find "the docs about X" without exact keyword
      matches.
    </p>

    <h2>Context windows</h2>
    <p>
      The context window is the maximum number of tokens (input + output) a model call can hold. Everything a RAG
      pipeline retrieves has to fit inside it, alongside the system prompt, the conversation history, and the
      question itself — which is why chunking and retrieval quality (Module 35) matter more as context grows, not
      less.
    </p>

    <h2>RAG vs. fine-tuning vs. long-context</h2>
    <p>
      Three ways to get a model to "know" your data: <strong>RAG</strong> (retrieve relevant chunks at query time and
      put them in the prompt), <strong>fine-tuning</strong> (bake knowledge/behavior into model weights), and
      <strong>long-context stuffing</strong> (paste everything into a huge context window). This curriculum is
      RAG-first because it's the cheapest to keep fresh — swap the index, not the model — but the trade-offs are
      revisited at every path level.
    </p>

    <h2>Try it in your flavor</h2>
    <FlavorTabs moduleId={moduleId} entries={entries} />

    <h2>Pitfalls</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Confusing "similar embedding" with "relevant answer" — similarity is necessary, not sufficient.</li>
      <li>Assuming a bigger context window removes the need for good retrieval — it just raises the cost of a bad one.</li>
      <li>Picking a fine-tune when the real problem is stale or missing data (RAG fixes that; fine-tuning doesn't).</li>
    </ul>
  </article>
  <ModuleQuiz moduleId={moduleId} />
  <ModuleFooterNav moduleId={moduleId} />
</BaseLayout>
